05940nam a22006495i 9780776628554DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807766285547 a10.1515/97807766285542doi  a(DE-B1597)668092  a(OCoLC)1419788517  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.C2bW4887 2019 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a305.897/0712231 aWiddowson, Frances, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeparate but Unequal :bHow Parallelist Ideology Conceals Indigenous Dependency /cFrances Widdowson. 1aOttawa : bUniversity of Ottawa Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Public Policy00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tINTRODUCTION Separate but Unequal -- tPART I: PARALLELIST IDEOLOGY AND THEORIZING INDIGENOUS DEPENDENCY -- tCHAPTER ONE The Parallelist View of Indigenous Dependency -- tCHAPTER TWO Postmodern “Conceptions of History” -- tCHAPTER THREE “Diversity” and the Obscuring of Developmental Differences -- tCHAPTER FOUR Postcolonialism and the Combination of Uneven Development -- tPART II: THE HISTORICAL AND MATERIAL ROOTS OF INDIGENOUS DEPENDENCY -- tCHAPTER FIVE Mercantile “Co-operation” during the Fur Trade -- tCHAPTER SIX Displacement and the Limits of Industrial Assimilation -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Negotiating a Renewed Dependency in Late Capitalism -- tCHAPTER EIGHT Laying Foundations for Overcoming Indigenous Dependency -- tCONCLUSION Understanding the Separation that Reflects Inequality -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSeparate but Unequal provides an in-depth critique of the ideology of parallelism—the prevailing view that Indigenous cultures and the wider Canadian society should exist separately from one another in a “nation-to-nation” relationship. Using the Final Report of the Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples as an example, this historical and material analysis shows how the single-minded pursuit of parallelism will not result in a more balanced relationship between Indigenous and non-Indigenous peoples. On the contrary, it merely restores archaic economic, political, and ideological forms that will continue to isolate the Indigenous population. This book provides an alternative framework for examining Indigenous dependency. This new perspective—the political economy of neotribal rentierism—shows that Indigenous Peoples’ circumstances have been inextricably linked to the development of capitalism in Canada. While Indigenous Peoples were integral participants in the fur trade, the transition from mercantilism to industrial capitalism led to their marginalization. This book is published in English. - Separate but Unequal fournit une analyse approfondie de l’idéologie du parallélisme – la vision dominante selon laquelle les cultures autochtones et la société canadienne en général devraient vivre séparément les unes des autres dans une relation de nation à nation. En s’appuyant sur le rapport final de la Commission royale sur les peuples autochtones, cette analyse historique et matérielle montre que les propositions parallélistes visant à accroître l’autonomie des Autochtones dans tous les aspects des politiques publiques ne se solderont pas en une relation plus équilibrée entre peuples autochtones et non autochtones, étant donné qu’elles ne font que rétablir des formes économiques, politiques et idéologiques archaïques qui continueront d’isoler la population autochtone. Elle propose de recadrer la question de la dépendance autochtone en ayant recours à la notion de rentiérisme néotribal. Ce cadre d’économie politique met en lumière le fait que les conditions des peuples autochtones ont été inextricablement liées au développement du capitalisme au Canada. Ce livre est publié en anglais.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxEconomic conditions. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxEconomic conditions. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh  aIndigenous peoples.  aNeotribal rentierism.  aParallelism.  aPolitical economy.  aRoyal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780776628554?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780776628554423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780776628554/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles